# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: anthony-crosland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on Thursday 23 February 1950, and was the first after a full term of a majority Labour Party government.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] It was also the first general election after the abolition of plural voting and university constituencies.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The general election saw Labour returned to power, but its majority was dramatically reduced from 146 seats to just 5, with a sizeable swing towards the Conservative Party, which gained 90 seats.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Turnout in this general election increased to 83.9%, the highest turnout in a United Kingdom general election under universal suffrage, and represented an increase of 11.1 percentage points from the 72.8% turnout in 1945.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The 1950 general election was also the first to be covered on television.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] (No recording was made of the live broadcast; this was the standard practice at the time.) Richard Dimbleby hosted the BBC coverage of the election, which he would later do again for the 1951, 1955, 1959 and the 1964 general elections.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] On this occasion, Dimbleby was joined in the BBC Alexandra Palace studios by R.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] McCallum, Fellow of Pembroke College, Oxford, and author of *The British General Election of 1945*, and David Butler, research student of Nuffield College.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The programme ran from 10:45 pm until just after 1:00 am.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Another general election was called in the following year, which the Conservatives won, restoring Winston Churchill as Prime Minister after six years in opposition.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour had governed the nation ever since their landslide in 1945.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Britain was confronted with severe economic challenges: the country faced a large national debt, its industries were weakened, and there were many shortages of food and raw materials.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] As a result, the Labour government continued rationing, and austerity was implemented, relying heavily on American loans and the Marshall Plan.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] While these measures were enacted to contain inflationary pressures, the British public suffered a fatigue.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] This prevented the Labour government from implementing some of its ambitious programmes.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Before the general election, major significant changes to the electoral system had occurred, including the abolition of plural voting by the Representation of the People Act 1948, and a major reorganisation of constituencies by the House of Commons (Redistribution of Seats) Act 1949.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Eleven new English seats were created and six were abolished, and there were over 170 major alterations to constituencies across the country.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Prime Minister Clement Attlee planned to call a summer general election.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] However, his Chancellor of the Exchequer, Stafford Cripps, refused to present a budget before a general election.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] As a result, Attlee was persuaded to call a February general election.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Parliament was dissolved on 3 February 1950.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives, having recovered from their landslide election defeat in 1945, accepted the broad framework of the welfare state and nationalisation that had taken place under the Attlee government, which included the National Health Service and the mixed economy.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservative manifesto, *This Is The Road*, accepted the new welfare state's foundations but criticised what it saw as the loss of freedoms and aspirations under Labour, with Churchill claiming Attlee had not "levelled up" but had actually "levelled down".
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The campaign essentially focused on the possible future nationalisation of other sectors and industries, which was opposed by the Conservatives but supported by Labour.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberals essentially viewed the struggle between the two parties on this issue as a class struggle.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Party fielded 475 candidates, more than at any general election since 1929.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Liberal Party leader Clement Davies felt that the party had been at a disadvantage at the 1945 general election when they ran fewer candidates than needed to form a government.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Davies arranged for the cost of running extra candidates to be offset by the party taking out insurance with Lloyd's of London against more than fifty candidates losing their deposits.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] A total of 319 Liberal candidates lost their deposits, a record number until the 2015 general election, when candidates for the Liberal Democrats lost 335 deposits at the general election held in that year.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] In the end, Labour lost 78 seats and its majority was reduced from 146 seats to just 5 seats.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives recovered significantly, seeing a resurgence in their support: they gained 90 seats and saw their vote share improve by 4.3 percentage points.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] With such a slender majority, Attlee had very little room for political manoeuvring, and passing legislation became difficult, with continued austerity and rationing straining Attlee's government from public support.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] As a result, seeking a better mandate, a general election was called the following year.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] However, despite winning the most votes (48.8% and 13,948,385 votes), they lost 20 seats, and Churchill was returned to power with a majority of 17 seats.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Analysis showed that Labour suffered huge losses of seats due to a "revolt of the suburbs", with substantial swings against them among Middle England voters in London, the Home Counties, Essex and Middlesex.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The effects of the Labour government's continued austerity and inflation had a negative effect for middle-income voters, with rationing of basic foods like bread and powdered egg proving incredibly unpopular.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] While campaigning in Leicester, Attlee was met with "catcalls" and chants of "vermin" while Hugh Gaitskell observed there was "a collection of grievances among the lower middle class and middle class" against Labour.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] The election began the factionalization of the Labour Party into the Bevanite and Gaitskellite factions.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the general election, Hugh Gaitskell blamed Aneurin Bevan for their party's disappointing performance, which led to a growing rift between the two.
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Prominent personalities entering Parliament in this election included Edward Heath (Bexley), Jo Grimond (Orkney and Shetland), Enoch Powell (Wolverhampton South West), Reginald Maudling (Barnet) and Iain Macleod (Enfield West).
[src:anthony-crosland/1950-united-kingdom-general-election] Scottish politician Willie Gallacher lost his West Fife seat to Labour; he was the last MP in Parliament for the Communist Party of Great Britain.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on Thursday 26 May 1955.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] It was a snap election: Anthony Eden called the election after succeeding Winston Churchill in April 1955 to secure a mandate.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] The government won a 60-seat majority, achieving the highest post-war party vote share.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] It was the first election under Queen Elizabeth II.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] In 1951, the Conservative Party had returned to power for the first time since World War II and increased its popularity by accepting the mixed economy and welfare state created by the previous Labour Party government.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] It also was lauded for its economic policy after ending rationing, improving foreign trade, and even outperforming Labour in the construction of public housing.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] The "giveaway budget" of Chancellor Rab Butler prior to the election also improved the popularity of the Conservative Party.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] On election day, the *Daily Mirror* had printed the front-page headline "Don't Let the Tories Cheat Our Children", urging its readers to elect Labour on the basis that it had "built a better Britain for us all".
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] The BBC later described the election as the "dullest" after World War II.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] The *Daily Express* wrote that the British people were more interested in Princess Margaret's romance with Peter Townsend.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour Party, then in its twentieth year of leadership under Clement Attlee, steadily lost ground owing to infighting between the left-wing (Bevanites) and the right-wing (Gaitskellites), resulting in an unclear election message.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] It pledged equal pay for women, renationalisation of the steel industry and road haulage, comprehensive secondary education, and vague guarantees of greater industrial democracy and workers' control of nationalised industries as demanded by Bevanites but otherwise offered little new policy.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] It was the fifth and last general election fought by Labour leader Clement Attlee, who by this time was 72 years old.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] Eden had only become Leader of the Conservative Party a few weeks before the election, following the retirement of former Prime Minister Winston Churchill, but he had long been considered the heir apparent to the Conservative leadership.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] Eden called a dissolution of parliament and a new general election as soon as he took office in April 1955.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives were hoping to take advantage of the end of food rationing and the positive atmosphere created by the coronation of Elizabeth II in 1953.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] Eden himself was telegenic (although not as great a public speaker as Churchill, who was now infirm and 80 years old) and gradual economic growth benefited the party greatly.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was fought on new boundaries, with five seats added to the 625 fought in 1951.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] The result showed very little change from 1951, with fewer than 25 seats changing hands and only a small swing from Labour to the Conservatives.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] The only real highlight of the night was in Northern Ireland, where Sinn Féin won two seats at a UK election for the first time since 1918 (before the secession of Southern Ireland).
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour Party suffered at this time from deep internal divisions, yet for it this election was not the disaster it could have been.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] Although little changed, this was a strong victory for the Conservatives, who won the largest share of seats for a single party at a post-war general election.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] It became the first party since the passage of the Reform Act 1867 to increase its parliamentary majority after a term in office.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Party had yet another poor performance, only slightly improving their popular vote total from the previous election, and again winning just six seats.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] The poor national showing was widely viewed as the death knell for the embattled leadership of Clement Davies, who resigned the following year and was replaced by Grimond.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] Future Labour leader Michael Foot lost his seat of Plymouth Devonport at this election; he returned for Ebbw Vale at a 1960 by-election.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] For the first time, television took a prominent role in the campaign; this is the earliest UK general election of which television coverage survives (the 1950 and 1951 election nights were broadcast on television live, but the footage was not recorded).
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] Only three hours of the coverage, presented by Richard Dimbleby, was kept; this was rebroadcast on BBC Parliament on the fiftieth and sixtieth anniversaries of the date of the election.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] Sinn Féin winner overturned on petition for a criminal conviction.
[src:anthony-crosland/1955-united-kingdom-general-election] The second-placed candidate, an Ulster Unionist, was awarded the seat.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on Thursday, 8 October 1959.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservative Party under the leadership of incumbent prime minister Harold Macmillan won a landslide victory with a majority of 100 seats.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] This was their third election victory in a row.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives won the largest number of votes in Scotland, but narrowly failed to win the most seats in that country.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] They have not made either achievement ever since.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Both Jeremy Thorpe, a future Liberal leader, and Margaret Thatcher, a future Conservative leader and eventually Prime Minister, first entered the House of Commons following this election.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Following the Suez Crisis in 1956, Anthony Eden, the Conservative Prime Minister, became unpopular.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] He resigned early in 1957, and was succeeded by Chancellor of the Exchequer Harold Macmillan.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] At that point, the Labour Party, whose leader Hugh Gaitskell had succeeded Clement Attlee following the 1955 general election, enjoyed large leads in opinion polls over the Conservative Party, and it looked as if Labour would win.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Party also had a new leader, Jo Grimond, so all three parties contested the election with a new leader at the helm.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] However, the Conservatives enjoyed an upturn in fortunes as the economy quickly recovered from the Recession of 1958 under Macmillan's leadership, and his personal approval ratings remained high.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] At the same time, the Labour Party's popularity suffered due to the rise of industrial disputes in the 1950s and controversies over the Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] By September 1958, the Conservatives had moved ahead of Labour in the opinion polls.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Parliament was dissolved on 18 September 1959.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] All the three main parties had changed leadership since the previous election.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives fought under the slogan "Life is better with the Conservatives, don't let Labour ruin it" and were boosted by a pre-election economic boom.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Macmillan very effectively "summed up" the mood of the British public when he said that most of the people had "never had it so good".
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Macmillan was very popular, and was described as a politician of the centre ground; in the 1930s he had represented a constituency in northern England (Stockton-on-Tees), which had experienced large-scale unemployment and poverty during the Great Depression.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] The first week of polling put the Conservatives ahead of Labour by over 5%, but this narrowed as the campaign continued.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour Party fought a generally effective campaign, with television broadcasts masterminded by Tony Benn under the umbrella of their manifesto entitled *Britain Belongs to You*, which accused the Conservatives of complacency over the growing gap between rich and poor.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour's manifesto pledged to reverse reductions in welfare benefits, pensions, and National Health Service expenditure; renationalize the steel industry and road haulage; reform secondary education; expand consumer protections; and create the Welsh Office.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] It notably promised not to fully nationalise industries which were performing efficiently and profitably, pivoting away from its earlier emphasis on socialism towards welfare capitalism.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Hugh Gaitskell made a mistake in declaring that a Labour government would not raise taxes if it came to power—even though the Labour manifesto contained pledges to increase spending; especially to increase pensions.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Although Gaitskell argued revenue would be provided by economic growth, this led some voters to doubt Labour's spending plans, and is cited as a key reason for their defeat.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Early on during election night, it became clear that the Conservative Party had been returned to government with an increased majority, performing better than it had been expected to.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] For the fourth general election in a row, the Conservatives increased their number of seats, despite experiencing a slight decrease in their share of the vote.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Future Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher was elected to the House of Commons for the first time as the MP for Finchley, where she would represent until her retirement from politics 33 years later at the 1992 general election.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] For Labour, the result was disappointing; despite appearing more united than they had in recent years under Gaitskell's leadership, the party suffered a third consecutive defeat.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] James Callaghan believed that the Conservatives increased their majority in part because working-class Labour voters were still angry at the party for opposing the Suez conflict.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Political scientists Mark Abrams and Richard Rose blamed Labour's electoral losses from 1959 onwards on an "embourgeoisement" in which British voters identified increasingly with the middle class, leaving Labour's appeals to the working class less effective.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Another key factor was the decline of support of younger voters after 1955, although older voters over the age of 65 increased support for the party in 1959 because of its pledges to expand pensions.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] While the Liberal Party earned more than twice as many votes compared to the previous general election, this was largely the result of them nominating nearly double the number of candidates that they did four years prior; their average number of votes-per-candidate only slightly improved.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Future Liberal Party Leader Jeremy Thorpe was elected to Parliament for the first time, as the MP for North Devon.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] The *Daily Mirror*, despite being a staunch supporter of the Labour Party, wished Macmillan "good luck" on its front page following his election victory.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] The BBC Television Service's election coverage, presented by Richard Dimbleby, was shown on BBC Parliament on 9 October 2009 to mark the fiftieth anniversary of the election and again on 9 October 2019 to mark the sixtieth anniversary.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] The 1959 general election was the first election to be covered by commercial television in the United Kingdom.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] The ITV network provided election night coverage from the studios of Independent Television News (ITN) in London, with ITV given permission by the Independent Television Authority to use all of the ITV companies on air in 1959 for election links to the main studio in London.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Ian Trethowan was the presenter for the ITV coverage.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Sinn Féin winner in 1955 overturned on petition.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] This candidate later defected to the Ulster Unionists.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Sinn Féin winner in 1955 overturned on petition for criminal conviction.
[src:anthony-crosland/1959-united-kingdom-general-election] Seat had been won by the Liberals in a 1958 by-election.
[src:anthony-crosland/1972-labour-party-deputy-leadership-election] The **1972 Labour Party deputy leadership election** took place in April 1972 after Roy Jenkins resigned as deputy leader over the decision to hold a referendum on Britain's entry into the Common Market.
[src:anthony-crosland/1972-labour-party-deputy-leadership-election] Edward Short, formerly Education Secretary in the government of Harold Wilson, was regarded as a "unity" candidate, and won the election over his main rival, the left-winger Michael Foot, who had unsuccessfully stood for the deputy leadership in 1970 and 1971.
[src:anthony-crosland/1972-labour-party-deputy-leadership-election] As a result of the first round, Crosland was eliminated.
[src:anthony-crosland/1972-labour-party-deputy-leadership-election] The remaining two candidates would face each other in a second round.
[src:anthony-crosland/1972-labour-party-deputy-leadership-election] The next day's *The Glasgow Herald* reported that both Short and Crosland attracted more votes than had been expected and that Short was the favourite to pick up most of Crosland's votes.
[src:anthony-crosland/1972-labour-party-deputy-leadership-election] Reporting on the result, *The Glasgow Herald'*s political correspondent John Warden stated that Short was "reckoned to be the least divisive of the three candidates for the post".
[src:anthony-crosland/1972-labour-party-deputy-leadership-election] The same report noted that Short called for "unity and toleration in the Labour Party" in the wake of his victory.
[src:anthony-crosland/1972-labour-party-deputy-leadership-election] An editorial in the same newspaper argued the result was a foregone conclusion after the first ballot, but warned that be settling for a compromise candidate "Labour may not have solved their difficulties".
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] The **1976 Labour Party leadership election** occurred when Harold Wilson resigned as Leader of the Labour Party and Prime Minister.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] It is the only occasion when the Labour Party, whilst in government, has had a leadership election with more than one candidate.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] It was also the first time a governing party had chosen a Prime Minister through exhaustive ballots while in office.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] The new leader was elected by members of the Parliamentary Labour Party.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] In the wake of the news of Wilson's decision to resign, Callaghan was reported as being the favourite to succeed him.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] Political journalist Geoffrey Parkhouse wrote that "Barring a sensation, James Callaghan will be the next Prime Minister".
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] He argued that the timing favoured Callaghan, with Denis Healey caught up in budget work and having alienated the left wing of the Labour Party after attacking the Tribune group in a recent speech.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] He doubted whether Crosland or Jenkins would stand, as they were likely to fare better under a Callaghan premiership than they had under Wilson.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] As a result of the first ballot, Crosland was eliminated, while Jenkins and Benn withdrew from the contest.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] The remaining three candidates would face each other in a second ballot, five days later.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] Benn recommended that his supporters vote for Michael Foot.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] It was reported in *The Glasgow Herald* that Jenkins had withdrawn, despite finishing third, as he had concluded he could not improve on his 56 votes.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] Indeed, that result was a disappointment to him, as he had expected to receive at least 68 votes.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] Most of his advisors agreed with his decision to withdraw, though one, Dickson Mabon, attempted to convince him to stay in the contest.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] In contrast, Denis Healey, despite finishing behind both Jenkins and Benn, reckoned he could pick up votes from many parts of the party.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] The *Herald* also characterised the second round of the contest as being to determine who would face Foot in the final ballot, and believed Healey had a chance of pulling ahead of Callaghan.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] No candidate achieved an absolute majority; hence, the candidate with the lowest number of votes was eliminated (in this case Healey).
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] Callaghan was reported to be the favourite with his supporters, believing that it was impossible that the left-wing Foot could win the votes of more than half of those who had previously supported the right-wing Healey.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] However, Foot supporter John Silkin believed that 26 Healey voters would back Foot, more than enough for him to emerge victorious.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] A final run-off ballot was held six days later.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] He confirmed that Denis Healey would remain chancellor of the exchequer, signalling continuity in economic policy and a renewed commitment to tackling inflation as the government’s central priority.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] In his first television broadcast as prime minister, Callaghan warned that Britain faced “no soft option” and could not sustain its living standards through borrowing, emphasising that inflation must be reduced before unemployment could be effectively addressed.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] The leadership transition was widely described as orderly and democratic, with defeated candidates pledging loyalty.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-labour-party-leadership-election] However, the government’s parliamentary position was weakened almost immediately by the death of Labour minister Brian O'Malley, which removed its overall Commons majority.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 2, 1976.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic ticket of former Georgia governor Jimmy Carter and Minnesota senior senator Walter Mondale narrowly defeated the Republican ticket of incumbent president Gerald Ford and Kansas junior senator Bob Dole.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first presidential election since 1932 in which the incumbent was defeated, as well as the only one of the six presidential elections from 1968 to 1988 to have the Democratic Party ticket win.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford ascended to the presidency when Richard Nixon resigned in 1974 in the wake of the Watergate scandal, which badly damaged the Republican Party and its electoral prospects.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford previously served as Nixon's second vice president after his first vice president, Spiro Agnew, resigned in 1973 due to a bribery scandal.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford promised to continue Nixon's political agenda and govern as a moderate Republican, causing considerable backlash from the conservative wing of his party.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford narrowly prevailed against former California governor Ronald Reagan in the Republican primaries.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter was unknown outside of his home state of Georgia at the start of the Democratic primaries, but he emerged as the front-runner after his victories in the first set of primaries.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Campaigning as a political moderate within his own party and as a Washington outsider, Carter defeated numerous opponents to clinch the Democratic nomination.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford pursued a "Rose Garden strategy" in which he sought to portray himself as an experienced leader focused on fulfilling his role as chief executive.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] On the other hand, Carter emphasized his status as a reformer who was "untainted" by Washington.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Saddled with a poor economy, the fall of South Vietnam, and the political fallout from the Watergate scandal, including his unpopular pardon of Richard Nixon, Ford trailed by a wide margin in polls taken after Carter's formal nomination in July 1976.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford's polling rebounded after a strong performance in the first presidential debate, and the race was close on election day.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter won the election with 297 Electoral College votes and took 50.1% of the popular vote.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] He carried several Midwestern and Northeastern states along with every state in the Deep South, becoming the first Democrat to accomplish this feat since Franklin D.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter's narrow victories in Ohio and Wisconsin, which carried a combined 36 electoral votes, were crucial to his win.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Meanwhile, Ford swept the West Coast and Mountain states and took 48.0% of the popular vote.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford became the first president to have served without ever winning a national election as president or vice president.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] His loss to Carter was due in part to the backlash against Republican candidates nationwide in the wake of the Watergate scandal, a trend that became apparent in the 1974 elections.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The surprise winner of the 1976 Democratic presidential nomination was Jimmy Carter, a former state senator and governor of Georgia.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] When the primaries began, Carter was little-known at the national level, and many political pundits regarded a number of better-known candidates, such as Senator Henry M.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson from Washington, Representative Morris Udall from Arizona, Governor George Wallace of Alabama, and California Governor Jerry Brown, as the favorites for the nomination.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] However, in the wake of the Watergate scandal, Carter realized that his status as a Washington outsider, political centrist, and moderate reformer could give him an advantage over his better-known establishment rivals.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter also took advantage of the record number of state primaries and caucuses in 1976 to eliminate his better-known rivals one-by-one.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson made a fateful decision not to compete in the early Iowa caucus and New Hampshire primary, which Jimmy Carter won after liberals split their votes among four other candidates.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Though Jackson went on to win the Massachusetts and New York primaries, he was forced to quit the race on May 1, after losing the critical Pennsylvania primary to Carter by twelve percentage points.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter then defeated Governor Wallace, his main conservative challenger, by a wide margin in the North Carolina primary, forcing Wallace to end his campaign.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Representative Udall, a liberal, then became Carter's main challenger.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] He finished second to Carter in the New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Wisconsin, New York, Michigan, South Dakota, and Ohio primaries, and won the caucuses in his home state of Arizona, while running even with Carter in the New Mexico caucuses.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] However, the fact that Udall finished second to Carter in most of these races meant that Carter steadily accumulated more delegates for the nomination than Udall did.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] As Carter closed in on the nomination, an "ABC" ("Anybody But Carter") movement started among Northern and Western liberal Democrats who worried that Carter's Southern upbringing would make him too conservative for the Democratic Party.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The leaders of the "ABC" movement, Idaho Senator Frank Church and California Governor Jerry Brown, both announced their candidacies for the Democratic nomination, and defeated Carter in several late primaries.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] However, their campaigns started too late to prevent Carter from gathering the remaining delegates he needed to capture the nomination.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] By June 1976, Carter had captured more than enough delegates to win the Democratic nomination.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] At the 1976 Democratic National Convention, Carter easily won the nomination on the first ballot; Udall finished in second place.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter then chose Minnesota Senator Walter Mondale, a liberal, as his running mate.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The contest for the Republican Party's presidential nomination in 1976 was between two serious candidates: incumbent president Gerald Ford, a member of the party's moderate wing, and former governor of California Ronald Reagan, a member of the party's conservative wing.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The presidential primary campaign between the two men was hard-fought and relatively even; by the start of the Republican Convention in August 1976, the race for the nomination was still too close to call.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The 1976 Republican Convention was the last political convention to open with the presidential nomination still being undecided until the actual balloting at the convention.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The following graph depicts the standing of each candidate in the poll aggregators from January 1976 to Election Day.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] One of the advantages Ford held over Carter as the general election campaign began was his presidential privilege to preside over events celebrating the United States Bicentennial; this often resulted in favorable publicity for Ford.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] C., fireworks display on the Fourth of July, which was televised nationally.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] On July 7, 1976, the President and First Lady served as hosts at a White House state dinner for Queen Elizabeth II and Prince Philip of the United Kingdom, which was televised on the Public Broadcasting Service (PBS) network.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] These events were part of Ford's "Rose Garden" strategy to win the election, meaning that instead of appearing as a typical politician, Ford presented himself as a "tested leader" who was busily fulfilling the role of national leader and chief executive.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Not until October did Ford leave the White House to actively campaign across the nation.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter ran as a reformer who was "untainted" by Washington political scandals, which many voters found attractive in the wake of the Watergate scandal that had led to President Richard Nixon's resignation.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford, although personally unconnected with Watergate, was seen by many as too close to the discredited Nixon administration, especially after he granted Nixon a presidential pardon for any crimes he might have committed during his term of office.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford's pardon of Nixon caused his popularity, as measured by public opinion polls, to plummet.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford's refusal to explain his reasons for pardoning Nixon publicly (he would do so in his memoirs several years later), also hurt his image.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford unsuccessfully asked Congress to end the 1950s-era price controls on natural gas, which had caused a dwindling of American natural gas reserves after the 1973 oil crisis.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter stated during his campaign that he opposed the ending of the price controls and thought such a move would be "disastrous".
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] After the Democratic National Convention, Carter held a 33-point lead over Ford in the polls.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] However, as the campaign continued, the race greatly tightened.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] During the campaign *Playboy* magazine published a controversial interview with Carter; in the interview, Carter admitted to having "lusted in my heart" for women other than his wife and used the word "screw," which cut into his support among women and evangelical Christians.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] On September 23, Ford performed well in what was the first televised presidential debate since 1960.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Polls taken after the debate showed that most viewers felt that Ford was the winner.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter was also hurt by Ford's charges that he lacked the necessary experience to be an effective national leader and that he was vague on many issues.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] However, Ford also committed a costly blunder in the campaign that halted his momentum.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] During the second presidential debate on October 6, Ford stumbled when he asserted that "there is no Soviet domination of Eastern Europe, and there never will be under a Ford administration".
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] He added that he did not "believe that the Poles consider themselves dominated by the Soviet Union", and made the same claim with regard to Yugoslavia and Romania (Yugoslavia was not a Warsaw Pact member).
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford refused to retract his statement for almost a week after the debate, causing his surge in the polls to stall and allowing Carter to maintain a slight lead in the polls.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] A vice-presidential debate, the first formal one of its kind, between Bob Dole and Walter Mondale also hurt the Republican ticket when Dole asserted that military unpreparedness on the part of Democratic presidents was responsible for all of the wars the U.S. had fought in the 20th century.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Dole, a World War II veteran, noted that in every 20th-century war, from World War I to the Vietnam War, a Democrat had been president.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Dole then pointed out that the number of U.S. casualties in "Democrat wars" was roughly equal to the population of Detroit.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Many voters felt that Dole's criticism was unfairly harsh, and that his dispassionate delivery made him seem cold.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Years later, Dole would remark that he regretted the comment, believing that it had hurt the Republican ticket.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] One factor that did help Ford in the closing days of the campaign was a series of popular television appearances he did with Joe Garagiola, a retired baseball player for the St.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Louis Cardinals and a well-known announcer for NBC Sports.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Garagiola and Ford appeared in a number of shows in several large cities.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] During the show, Garagiola would ask Ford questions about his life and beliefs; the shows were so informal, relaxed, and laid-back that some television critics labelled them the "Joe and Jerry Show".
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford and Garagiola obviously enjoyed one another's company, and they remained friends after the election was over.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] There were three presidential debates and one vice presidential debate during the 1976 general election.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Despite his campaign's blunders, President Ford managed to close the remaining gap in the polls, and by election day, the race was judged to be even.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] It took most of that night and the following morning to determine the winner.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] It was not until 3:30 am EST that NBC was able to declare that Carter had carried Mississippi and had thus accumulated more than the 270 electoral votes needed to win.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Seconds later, ABC also declared Carter the winner, based on projections for Carter in Wisconsin and Hawaii, while CBS announced Carter's victory at 3:45 am.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter defeated Ford by two percentage points in the national popular vote.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The electoral vote was the closest since 1916; Carter carried 23 states, with 297 electoral votes, while Ford won 27 states, with 240 electoral votes (one elector, future state Senator Mike Padden from Washington state, pledged to Ford, voted for Reagan).
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter's victory came primarily from his near-sweep of the South (he lost only Virginia and Oklahoma), and his narrow victories in large Northern states such as New York, Ohio, and Pennsylvania.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Ford did well in the West, carrying every state in that region, except for Hawaii.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The most tightly contested state in the election was Oregon, which Ford won by under 2,000 votes.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] By percentage of the vote, the states that secured Carter's victory were Wisconsin (1.68% margin) and Ohio (.27% margin).
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Had Ford won these states and all other states he carried, he would have won the presidency.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The 27 states he won were, and still are, the most states ever carried by a losing candidate for president.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Had Ford won the election, the provisions of the 22nd Amendment would have disqualified him from running again, as he served more than two years of Nixon's second term.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter became the first non-incumbent president representing a Southern state to be elected since Zachary Taylor in 1848.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] As a result of his loss, Ford became the most recent person to serve as president without ever being elected to the office, and the first since Chester A.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Both major-party vice-presidential nominees would later unsuccessfully run for President: Walter Mondale (Democratic) in 1984 and Bob Dole (Republican) in 1996.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter was the first Democratic presidential nominee since John F.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Kennedy in 1960 to carry states in the Deep South (Bill Clinton was the only Democrat since 1976 to carry more than one state from the Deep South, doing so in 1992), and the only one since Lyndon B.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Johnson in 1964 to carry a majority of all southern states.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter performed very strongly in his home state of Georgia, carrying 66.7% of the vote and every county in the state.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] His winning of 23 states was only the second time in history that the winner of the election won fewer than half the states (after 1960).
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] His 50.1% of the vote was the only time since 1964 that a Democrat managed to obtain an absolute majority of the popular vote in a presidential election until Barack Obama won 52.9% of the vote in 2008.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter is one of six Democrats since the American Civil War to obtain an absolute majority of the popular vote, the others being Samuel J.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the last time that a Democrat won the presidency without winning a number of modern blue states and swing states, specifically California, Connecticut, Illinois, Maine, Michigan, Nevada, New Hampshire, New Jersey, New Mexico, Oregon, Vermont, and Washington.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This is the only time a Democrat has won without New Mexico, as well as one of only two times it voted for a candidate who lost the popular vote, in addition to 2024.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Similarly, it is one of only three instances in which a Democrat won without Nevada (the others being the two elections of Grover Cleveland in 1884 and 1892).
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats did not win without Iowa again until 2020.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last time a winning Democrat won both Georgia and Florida.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] All future Democratic presidents won one of the two, but not both simultaneously.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] It was the first time in exactly 100 years when Florida and Virginia supported different candidates, and the first time since Oklahoma statehood in 1907 when Oklahoma and Tennessee did so.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the most recent election in which a losing Republican candidate carried any states in the Northeast.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] As Carter won 319 more counties than Ford, this election would mark the last time a Democrat won a majority of counties.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first election since 1916 in which the winning candidate won fewer than 300 electoral votes; this would not happen again until 2000.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Carter also remains the last Democrat to win a presidential election while winning fewer than 300 electoral votes.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the last time until 2024 in which the popular vote margin in all 50 states and the District of Columbia swung in the same direction from the previous election, and the most recent in which they all swung Democratic.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This is the last election in which an incumbent president ran with a running mate who was not the incumbent vice president.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This is the only election in which all four major presidential and vice presidential candidates would at some point be their party's nominee for president and lose.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] In addition to Ford losing this election, Carter would lose reelection to Reagan in 1980, Mondale would lose to President Reagan in 1984, and Dole would lose to President Bill Clinton in 1996.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] This election represents the second time that the winning candidate has received a majority of the electoral votes while the second-place candidate carried a majority of the states.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] It had previously happened in the 1960 election.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] The "margin" column shows the difference between the two leading candidates, and the "swing" column shows the margin swing from the respective party's nominee from 1972 to 1976.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Maine allowed its electoral votes to be split between candidates.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] Two electoral votes were awarded to the winner of the statewide race and one electoral vote to the winner of each congressional district.
[src:anthony-crosland/1976-united-states-presidential-election] With voters 30 years of age or older (born in 1946 or earlier) estimated by the exit poll to comprise 69% of the electorate, the Greatest Generation and the Silent Generation constituted the majority of the voting public.
[src:anthony-crosland/1977-great-grimsby-by-election] The **1977 by-election** for the **Great Grimsby** took place on 28 April 1977.
[src:anthony-crosland/1977-great-grimsby-by-election] It was caused by the death in February of Anthony Crosland, and was retained for Labour by Austin Mitchell.
[src:anthony-crosland/1977-great-grimsby-by-election] It took place on the same day as the Labour defeat in Ashfield.
[src:anthony-crosland/1977-great-grimsby-by-election] The result in Grimsby and Ashfield were seen as a surprise as they were the opposite of what had been expected.
[src:anthony-crosland/1977-great-grimsby-by-election] Grimsby had been expected to fall to the Conservatives, while Labour had expected to hold Ashfield, which they had held by a much larger majority.
[src:anthony-crosland/1977-great-grimsby-by-election] In the event while there was a swing of 20.9% to the Conservatives in Ashfield, which was just enough to win the seat, the Labour to Conservative swing in Grimsby was only 7% and Mitchell managed to poll more votes than Crosland had at the last election.
[src:anthony-crosland/1977-great-grimsby-by-election] The Liberal Party lost its deposit in both Grimsby and Ashfield, the third time this had happened at a by-election following the 1977 Lib-Lab Pact.
[src:anthony-crosland/1977-great-grimsby-by-election] At the next election, in 1979, Mitchell increased his majority to 6,241 votes.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Having served as Member of Parliament (MP) for South Gloucestershire from 1950 to 1955, Crosland returned to Parliament for Great Grimsby (1959–1977).
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] During Harold Wilson's governments of 1964–1970 he served as Economic Secretary to the Treasury (1964), then Minister of State for Economic Affairs (1964–1965).
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Entering the Cabinet as Secretary of State for Education and Science (1965–1967), he led the Labour campaign to replace grammar schools with comprehensive schools that did not use the eleven-plus for the selection of pupils.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He later served as President of the Board of Trade (1967–1969), then Secretary of State for Local Government and Regional Planning (1969–1970).
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] When Labour returned to power he served as Secretary of State for the Environment (1974–1976) and briefly as Foreign Secretary (1976–1977).
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] In that role he promoted détente with the Soviet Union.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He died suddenly in February 1977 of a cerebral haemorrhage, aged 58.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland was born at St Leonards-on-Sea in East Sussex.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] His father, Joseph Beardsall Crosland, was a senior official at the War Office, and his mother, Jessie Raven, was an academic.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Both of his parents were members of the Plymouth Brethren.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] His maternal grandfather was Frederick Edward Raven (1837–1903), founder of the Raven Exclusive Brethren and secretary of the Royal Naval College, Greenwich.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland later rejected his family's religion.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He grew up in north London and was educated at Highgate School and at Trinity College, Oxford, obtaining a second class honours degree in Classical Moderations in Greek and Latin Literature.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] In the spring of 1941, Crosland was commissioned in the Royal Welch Fusiliers, and in late 1942 he joined (as part of the 6th (Royal Welch) Parachute Battalion) the 2nd Parachute Brigade, which was part of the 1st Airborne Division.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] In September 1943, he participated in the landings at Taranto, Operation Slapstick.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland had his first direct experience of combat in Italy in December .
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He then became an intelligence officer gathering information for several months in the front line about troop movements at the Battle of Monte Cassino, and was also briefly involved in the Allied invasion of southern France as part of Operation Rugby in August 1944.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] After the war, Crosland returned to Oxford University and obtained first class honours in Philosophy, Politics and Economics, which he studied in 12 months; he also became President of the Oxford Union.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He then became a university don at Oxford, tutoring in Economics.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Notable people he taught at Oxford included Tony Benn, Norris McWhirter and Ross McWhirter.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland, who had been talent-spotted by Hugh Dalton, was chosen as a Labour candidate in December 1949 to fight the next general election.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He entered Parliament at the February 1950 general election, being returned for the South Gloucestershire constituency.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He held that seat until the 1955 general election, when he was defeated at Southampton Test.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland returned to the House of Commons at the 1959 general election when he was elected for Grimsby, which he would represent for the rest of his life.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He was, like Roy Jenkins and Denis Healey, a friend and protégé of Hugh Gaitskell, and together they were regarded as the "modernisers" of their day.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] From June 1960, Crosland played an important part in the establishment of the Campaign for Democratic Socialism, a right-wing grassroots group within the Labour Party, created, in part, as a response to the debates around the Left's advocacy of unilateral nuclear disarmament and Clause IV.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] However, Crosland was against Gaitskell's attempts to change Clause 4.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Even though they were from the same wing of the party, the thought of the Labour Party being led by the volatile George Brown appalled Crosland, but he also was a critic of Harold Wilson for his apparent lack of principles.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Just over two years earlier Wilson had challenged Gaitskell for the party leadership.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland nominated and voted for James Callaghan in the leadership contest caused by Gaitskell's death on 18 January 1963.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He rationalised his decision to back Callaghan on the basis that "We have to choose between a crook [Harold Wilson] and a drunk [George Brown]".
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] However, Callaghan was eliminated after obtaining 41 votes, the margin in votes between Wilson and Brown in the final ballot.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] With Callaghan eliminated, Crosland's second wife wrote in her 1982 biography, he voted for George Brown in the second ballot, although with zero enthusiasm, and with little interest about the result, as he was opposed to both of the candidates now standing for the party leadership.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Wilson won by 144 votes to Brown's 103 on 14 February 1963.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Although critical of Harold Wilson, and angry with him for his 1960 challenge to Gaitskell for the party leadership, Crosland respected him as a political operator.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Under Wilson, Crosland was first appointed Brown's deputy in October 1964.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] In November 1964 Crosland and Brown told Wilson and Callaghan that ruling out devaluation was a mistake in the face of the economic crisis then under way.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] However, Crosland was not Brown's deputy for long.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] On 22 January 1965, Wilson appointed Crosland Secretary of State for Education and Science.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] The ongoing campaign for Comprehensive schools in England and Wales gained a major boost with Circular 10/65, which as a statute rather than a Government Bill was controversial at the time, although a government motion in favour of the policy had been passed in January 1965.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland's policy gained approval from local government; by 1979 over 90% of pupils were in comprehensive schools.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] In her biography published in 1982, Susan Crosland said her husband had told her "If it's the last thing I do, I'm going to destroy every fucking grammar school in England.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Another major educational change was that presaged by his speech at Woolwich Polytechnic (now Greenwich University) establishing a 'binary system' of higher education, in which universities would be joined by polytechnic institutions which concentrated on high-level vocational skills.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] In October 1966, a committee of ministers in the Labour government decided to increase university fees for overseas students.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Two months later Crosland announced their decision which treated Commonwealth students for the first time as if they were foreign.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Widespread protests, which erupted immediately, soon united a large number of influential people from across a wide spectrum from left-wing militant students to mildly conservative vice-chancellors.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland subsequently served as President of the Board of Trade from September 1967 to October 1969.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He was deeply disappointed not to have been made Chancellor of the Exchequer after the November 1967 cabinet reshuffle which followed the devaluation of the pound.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Then he became Secretary of State for Local Government and Regional Planning until the election defeat of June 1970.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland was seen as a leader and intellectual guru of the "right wing" or "social democratic" wing of the Labour Party in the 1970s.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] In April 1972, he stood for the deputy leadership of the party after Roy Jenkins resigned.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He polled 61 votes of the Parliamentary Labour Party and was eliminated in the first round.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] The contest was eventually won by Edward Short, who defeated Michael Foot.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland was embarrassed by the national press in January 1973 when it emerged he had been given a silver coffee pot donated by disgraced corrupt architect John Poulson when opening a school in Bradford in January 1966.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] It later transpired that the pot was only silver-plated, and therefore of trivial value.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] After Labour's return to power in March 1974, Crosland became Secretary of State for the Environment.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He was instrumental in changing Transport policy on British Rail to be a higher fare fast intercity passenger service rather than its previous role as a general freight common carrier.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He contested the leadership in March 1976 following Wilson's resignation, but polled only 17 votes and finished bottom of the poll.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] After his elimination, he switched his support to the eventual winner James Callaghan, who duly rewarded Crosland by appointing him Foreign Secretary on 8 April 1976.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland's time as foreign secretary was dominated by the Third Cod War and relations with Rhodesia.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland once quipped to his wife that "when I pop off and they cut open my heart, on it will be engraved 'fish' and 'Rhodesia'".
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Early in his life Crosland had numerous gay affairs, including allegedly with Roy Jenkins.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland benefited from the patronage of Hugh Dalton, who, in 1951, wrote to Richard Crossman: "Thinking of Tony, with all his youth and beauty and gaiety and charm...
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] I am more fond of that young man than I can put into words." According to Nicholas Davenport, Dalton's unrequited feelings for Crosland became an embarrassing joke within the Labour Party.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland married Hilary Sarson in November 1952, divorcing after five years, though the marriage had effectively ended after a year.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland had numerous affairs with other women.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He remarried on 7 February 1964 to Susan Catling, an American from Baltimore resident in London whom he had met in 1956, and, in contrast to his first marriage, this was very happy and contented.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Susan Crosland was a successful journalist and writer.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] There were no children of either marriage, although Crosland's second wife had two daughters from a previous marriage.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He persuaded his step-daughters to abandon their elite private schools to attend Holland Park Comprehensive.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Susan Crosland died on 26 February 2011.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland was a keen football fan and an avid viewer of the television show *Match of the Day*.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He insisted on taking the then American Secretary of State Henry Kissinger, a football fan, to Blundell Park to watch Grimsby Town play Gillingham in April 1976 when the two met for the first time.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] In December 1976, when Kissinger bowed out after the Republican defeat, he watched a football match with Crosland at Stamford Bridge between Chelsea and Wolverhampton Wanderers.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] After losing his seat in 1955, he wrote (as C.A.R.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland) *The Future of Socialism* which was published in autumn 1956.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] This became a seminal work for the moderate British left.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Labour revisionism was a powerful ideological tendency within the Party in the 1950s and 1960s, taking intellectual sustenance from the Crosland book, and political leadership from Hugh Gaitskell.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] The goal was to reformulate socialist principles, and bring the Labour Party policies up to date with the changing British society and economy.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Revisionism rejected the view that socialism ought to be primarily identified with the ownership of the means of production.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] That meant that continuous nationalisation was not a central goal.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] The focus should rather be on regulating the market, improving workers' pay and conditions, and public investment.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Second, was a series of political values focused on personal liberty, social welfare, and equality and "a more joyful society".
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Themes of destroying or overthrowing the rich and elite were downplayed in favour of policies of high taxation, more widespread educational opportunity, and expanded social services.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Revisionists insisted on the necessity of a market-oriented mixed economy with a central role for capitalism and entrepreneurship.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland was himself an active member of the Fabian Society, contributing to the *New Fabian Essays* collection, which saw the emerging generation of Labour thinkers and politicians attempt to set out a new programme for Labour following the Attlee governments of 1945 to 1951.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] In the 1951 essay "The Transition from Capitalism" he claimed that "by 1951 Britain had, in all the essentials, ceased to be a capitalist country" as a result of the establishment of the welfare state.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Or at least, if they are, some of us will fall by the wayside".
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Two further books of essays by Crosland were published: *The Conservative Enemy* (London, Cape, 1962) and *Socialism Now, and Other Essays* (London, Cape, 1974).
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland and his wife bought a converted mill at Adderbury in Oxfordshire in 1975, as well as having a home at Lansdowne Road in Notting Hill, London.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] On the afternoon of 13 February 1977, Crosland was at his home in Adderbury, working on a paper on the Rhodesian situation, and was planning that evening to complete a major foreign policy speech on détente.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] However, he suffered a massive cerebral haemorrhage and fell into a coma.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] He died six days later, on 19 February, at Radcliffe Infirmary in Oxford, aged 58.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] Crosland was succeeded as foreign secretary by David Owen, who delivered his speech to the Diplomatic Writers Association on 3 March 1977.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] The following day, Crosland's ashes were scattered at sea near Grimsby.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] His papers are held at the London School of Economics.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] The play *Gang of Three* was originally performed at the King's Head Theatre in London in 2025 and will tour the UK in 2026.
[src:anthony-crosland/anthony-crosland] The play examines the relationship between Denis Healey, Tony Crosland and Roy Jenkins and was written by Khan and Salinsky.
